emale":"1410–Deceased","1356–1427":"1356–1427","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1374":"1374","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1401":"1401","BEF 1374":"before 1374","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","Abt 1420":"about 1420","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","1429":"1429","circa 1400":"about 1400","1405":"1405","1339":"1339","1427":"1427","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England":"Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England","Elvetham, Hampshire, England":"Elvetham, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":8,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Esturnie was born in 1374, in Elvetham, Hampshire, England, her father, William de Sturmy, was 18 and her mother, Joan Stockhay, was 36. She married Sir Roger Seymour about 1400. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died about 1420, in Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1374–Abt 1420":"1374–umbes 1420","1374–1420":"1374–1420","–Female":"Surnud","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1401–1464":"1401–1464","1405–1440":"1405–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1356–1427":"1356–1427","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1374":"1374","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1401":"1401","BEF 1374":"enne 1374","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","Abt 1420":"umbes 1420","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","1429":"1429","circa 1400":"umbes 1400","1405":"1405","1339":"1339","1427":"1427","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England":"Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England","Elvetham, Hampshire, England":"Elvetham, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1374–Abt 1420":"1374–noin 1420","1374–1420":"1374–1420","–Female":"Kuollut","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1401–1464":"1401–1464","1405–1440":"1405–1440","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1356–1427":"1356–1427","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1374":"1374","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1401":"1401","BEF 1374":"ennen vuotta 1374","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","Abt 1420":"noin 1420","1464":"1464","1420":"1420","1429":"1429","circa 1400":"noin 1400","1405":"1405","1339":"1339","1427":"1427","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England":"Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England","Elvetham, Hampshire, England":"Elvetham, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1374–Abt 1420":"1374–environ 1420","1374–1420":"1374–1420","–Female":"Décédée","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1401–1464":